<!-- ═══ CONTROL ═══ -->
<section class="lineage-section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="lineage-header reveal d1">
      <p class="lineage-pillar-label">Pillar III — Control</p>
      <h2 class="lineage-pillar-name">Live Within Bounds</h2>
      <p class="lineage-pillar-tagline">What they wrote about what is yours and what is not.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d2">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Marcus Aurelius</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">121 – 180 AD · Emperor of Rome</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>You always own the option of having no opinion. There is never any need to get worked up or to trouble your soul about things you can't control.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book VI</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VII — <strong>Own Only What Is Yours.</strong> Marcus drew the same line that Grithos draws: your thoughts, your decisions, your effort, your character. Everything else belongs to the bounds. But where Marcus counseled calm acceptance, Grithos adds fire — you own what is yours, you fight for the outcome, and only when the bounds truly close the door do you redirect.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>The universe is change; our life is what our thoughts make it.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book IV</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VIII — <strong>Redirect Immediately.</strong> Marcus understood that the universe does not pause for your grief, your outrage, or your plans. It changes. Constantly. A Grithosian does not waste energy fighting change. You redirect — immediately, deliberately — toward what you can actually influence. The bounds are not your enemy. They are the structure God authored, and they are trustworthy.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Everything we hear is an opinion, not a fact. Everything we see is a perspective, not the truth.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book IV</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet IX — <strong>Trust the Bounds.</strong> Marcus knew that most of what troubles us is not reality — it is our interpretation of reality. The bounds are rational and consistent. God authored them that way. A Grithosian trusts the structure, even when the interpretation feels unbearable. Separate what happened from your story about what happened. The bounds hold. Trust them.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Benjamin Franklin</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1706 – 1790 · Founding Father, Inventor, Philosopher</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">A self-educated printer who became a scientist, diplomat, and architect of a nation. Franklin created a system of thirteen virtues and tracked his adherence to them daily in a small notebook — the original daily practice. He understood that character is not inherited. It is built, one disciplined day at a time.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>An investment in knowledge pays the best interest.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin, Poor Richard's Almanack</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VII — <strong>Own Only What Is Yours.</strong> Franklin understood that the only assets no one can take from you are the ones you build inside yourself — your knowledge, your character, your discipline. A Grithosian invests in what is truly theirs. Not possessions. Not titles. The things that compound quietly and last forever.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>By failing to prepare, you are preparing to fail.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is the discipline of Pillar III — <strong>live within bounds.</strong> Franklin did not leave virtue to chance. He tracked it. Daily. In a notebook he carried everywhere. A Grithosian does the same with the Daily Practice — one practice per day, every day. Discipline is not what you do when you feel like it. It is the structure you build so you do it regardless.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>I didn't fail the test. I just found 100 ways to do it wrong.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VIII — <strong>Redirect Immediately.</strong> Franklin failed constantly — business ventures, experiments, diplomatic efforts. He did not spiral. He redirected. Every failure was data. Every closed door was a map to the next open one. A Grithosian treats failure the same way: not as a verdict, but as a pivot point.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Epictetus</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">50 – 135 AD · Former Slave, Stoic Philosopher</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Make the best use of what is in your power, and take the rest as it happens.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Epictetus, Discourses, Book I</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VII — <strong>Own Only What Is Yours.</strong> This is the original statement of the control boundary. Epictetus drew the line twenty centuries ago — what is in your power and what is not. A Grithosian honors that line. You fight for everything within the bounds. You release everything outside them. That is not weakness. That is wisdom.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Man is not worried by real problems so much as by his imagined anxieties about real problems.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Epictetus, Discourses</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet IX — <strong>Trust the Bounds.</strong> Epictetus saw what anxiety really is — a war against things that haven't happened yet. The bounds are real. Your worry about the bounds is not. A Grithosian separates the actual threat from the imagined one, and works only on what is real.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Lao Tzu</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">6th Century BC · Chinese Philosopher, Author of the Tao Te Ching</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Lao Tzu — if he was one man and not a tradition given a name — is credited with writing the Tao Te Ching, eighty-one verses that have shaped Eastern philosophy for twenty-five centuries. He served as a record keeper in the Zhou dynasty court, watched civilization consume itself with ambition and control, and concluded that the greatest power lies in knowing what to release. He reportedly wrote the Tao Te Ching in a single sitting at a border gate, then walked into the mountains and was never seen again.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>When I let go of what I am, I become what I might be.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Lao Tzu, Tao Te Ching, Chapter 22 (translation by John C.H. Wu)</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VII — <strong>Own Only What Is Yours.</strong> Lao Tzu understood something most people spend a lifetime avoiding: you cannot become what you are meant to be while clinging to what you think you already are. A Grithosian releases the identity that no longer serves — the old story, the comfortable lie, the version of yourself that stopped growing. Own only what is truly yours: your character, your choices, your daily practice. Let the rest fall away.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>He who controls others may be powerful, but he who has mastered himself is mightier still.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Lao Tzu, Tao Te Ching, Chapter 33 (translation by Stephen Mitchell)</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VIII — <strong>Master the Impulse.</strong> Lao Tzu drew the sharpest possible line between external power and internal mastery. The world is full of people who can dominate a room and cannot dominate their own appetites. A Grithosian masters the impulse — the rage, the craving, the need to react before thinking. That mastery is mightier than any throne or title. It is the only power that cannot be taken from you.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Nature does not hurry, yet everything is accomplished.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Lao Tzu, Tao Te Ching, Chapter 73 (traditional attribution)</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet IX — <strong>Trust the Bounds.</strong> Lao Tzu saw what most of us refuse to see: the structure of existence is not broken. It does not need your anxiety to function. The seasons turn. The river finds the sea. A Grithosian trusts the bounds — not passively, but with the deep confidence that comes from understanding the architecture. God authored a system that works. Your job is to work within it, not to fight it. Nature does not hurry. Neither should your worry.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Confucius</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">551 – 479 BC · Chinese Philosopher, Teacher</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Confucius wandered for fourteen years trying to convince rulers to govern with virtue, was rejected by nearly all of them, and returned home to teach. His philosophy of self-cultivation, ritual discipline, and moral order shaped East Asian civilization for twenty-five centuries.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>By three methods we may learn wisdom: First, by reflection, which is noblest; Second, by imitation, which is easiest; and third by experience, which is the bitterest.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Confucius, Analects</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet IX — <strong>Trust the Bounds.</strong> Confucius understood that wisdom operates within structure — reflection, imitation, experience. A Grithosian trusts that each method has its place and season. The bounds of learning are not limitations. They are the framework that makes wisdom possible.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Ralph Waldo Emerson</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1803 – 1882 · Essayist, Philosopher, Poet</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Emerson left the ministry, buried his first wife and his young son, and rebuilt his life around one radical idea: trust yourself. He became the voice of American self-reliance and wrote essays that gave an entire nation permission to think for itself.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>What lies behind us and what lies before us are tiny matters compared to what lies within us.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Ralph Waldo Emerson, attributed, widely cited</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VII — <strong>Own Only What Is Yours.</strong> Emerson drew the line clearly — the past is gone, the future is uncertain, but what you carry within yourself is real and powerful right now. A Grithosian invests in that inner strength. It is the only asset that cannot be taken.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Henry David Thoreau</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1817 – 1862 · Writer, Naturalist, Philosopher</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Thoreau walked into the woods at Walden Pond to strip life down to its essentials and prove that most of what people chase is unnecessary. He went to jail rather than pay taxes supporting a war he opposed, and he wrote the essay on civil disobedience that later inspired Gandhi and King.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>The mass of men lead lives of quiet desperation.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Henry David Thoreau, Walden, Chapter 1, 1854</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VIII — <strong>Redirect Immediately.</strong> Thoreau saw that most people accept a life they do not want because they are afraid to change course. A Grithosian refuses quiet desperation. When you recognize that your current path is not yours, you redirect. Immediately. Thoreau walked to the woods. Where will you walk?
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Michel de Montaigne</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1533 – 1592 · French Essayist, Statesman</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Montaigne retired to his tower library at thirty-eight, invented the personal essay, and spent the rest of his life examining his own mind with ruthless honesty. He wrote about fear, death, cannibals, and kidney stones with equal candor — proving that self-knowledge is the hardest and most valuable discipline.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>We are all patchwork, and so shapeless and diverse in composition that each bit, each moment, plays its own game.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Michel de Montaigne, Essays, Book III, Chapter 2, "Of Repentance"</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VII — <strong>Own Only What Is Yours.</strong> Montaigne understood that you are not a fixed thing but a collection of moments, choices, and contradictions. A Grithosian owns the whole patchwork — the noble and the shameful, the strong and the weak. Integration, not perfection, is the goal.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Blaise Pascal</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1623 – 1662 · Mathematician, Physicist, Philosopher</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Pascal built the first mechanical calculator at nineteen, laid the foundations of probability theory, and then turned his genius toward the human condition. He argued that most of humanity's problems stem from the inability to sit quietly in a room — a diagnosis that has only grown more accurate with time.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>All of humanity's problems stem from man's inability to sit quietly in a room alone.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Blaise Pascal, Pensées, #139</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet IX — <strong>Trust the Bounds.</strong> Pascal identified the source of most human suffering — the inability to be still. A Grithosian practices stillness not as escape but as foundation. In the quiet room, you discover what is real and what is noise. The bounds become clear.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Baltasar Gracián</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1601 – 1658 · Spanish Jesuit Priest, Philosopher</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Gracián wrote The Art of Worldly Wisdom — three hundred maxims on how to navigate power, deception, and human nature without losing your soul. His own Jesuit order censored and punished him for publishing it, which only proved his point about the cost of speaking plainly.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Know how to refuse. One cannot say yes to everything, nor should one. To know how to refuse is as important as to know how to consent.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Baltasar Gracián, The Art of Worldly Wisdom, Maxim #77</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VII — <strong>Own Only What Is Yours.</strong> Gracián understood that boundaries are not selfish — they are strategic. A Grithosian says no to protect the yes that matters. Your energy, your time, your attention — these are finite. Guard them accordingly.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Thucydides</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">460 – 400 BC · Athenian General, Historian</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Thucydides commanded an Athenian fleet, lost a battle, was exiled for twenty years, and used that exile to write the most brutally honest account of war ever recorded. His History of the Peloponnesian War stripped away myth and propaganda to show power as it actually operates — and it hasn't aged a day.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>The secret to happiness is freedom... And the secret to freedom is courage.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Thucydides, attributed, widely cited in classical scholarship</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VIII — <strong>Redirect Immediately.</strong> Thucydides understood the chain: courage leads to freedom, freedom leads to happiness. A Grithosian has the courage to redirect when the current path no longer serves. The bounds may close one door, but courage opens another.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Plutarch</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">46 – 120 AD · Greek Biographer, Essayist, Priest</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Plutarch spent his life studying great men — pairing Greeks with Romans in his Parallel Lives to show that character, not circumstance, determines legacy. He served as a priest at Delphi and believed that biography, honestly told, was the most powerful tool for moral instruction.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>What we achieve inwardly will change outer reality.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Plutarch, attributed, widely cited</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VII — <strong>Own Only What Is Yours.</strong> Plutarch spent his life proving that character shapes destiny. A Grithosian works on the inside first — your habits, your thoughts, your daily practice. The outer world reflects the inner discipline. Always.
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

<!-- ═══ DEATH ═══ -->
<section class="lineage-section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="lineage-header reveal d1">
      <p class="lineage-pillar-label">Pillar IV — Death</p>
      <h2 class="lineage-pillar-name">Return to the Whole</h2>
      <p class="lineage-pillar-tagline">What they wrote about mortality and legacy.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d2">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Marcus Aurelius</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">121 – 180 AD · Emperor of Rome</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>It is not death that a man should fear, but he should fear never beginning to live.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book XII</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet X — <strong>Live Like You Will Die. Because You Will.</strong> Marcus did not fear death. He feared wasted life. A Grithosian uses mortality as the sharpest tool in the drawer — not as a threat, but as a lens. Every decision passes through it. Is this how you want to spend the time you have? If the answer is no, stop. Redirect. Now.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Loss is nothing else but change, and change is nature's delight.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book IX</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XI — <strong>Grieve Fully. Then Move.</strong> Marcus saw loss as transformation, not destruction. A Grithosian honors this — feel the grief completely, because it is proof of what you built. But do not live there. Loss is change. And change, as Marcus wrote, is woven into the fabric of existence. God authored the bounds to include both creation and loss. A Grithosian trusts both — and keeps moving.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Think of yourself as dead. You have lived your life. Now, take what's left and live it properly.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book VII</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XII — <strong>Build a Legacy That Stands in This Life.</strong> Marcus challenged himself to live as if he had already wasted his life — and now had one final chance to do it right. A Grithosian builds something that matters right here, right now. The people you lead, the truths you tell, the strength you use to protect others. That is your legacy in this life — and it matters regardless of what comes next.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d5">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>The soul becomes dyed with the color of its thoughts.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book V</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XII — <strong>Build a Legacy That Stands in This Life.</strong> Marcus understood that legacy is not built in a single grand gesture. It is built thought by thought, day by day. What you think about shapes who you become. A Grithosian guards their thoughts the way they guard their word — because both become permanent.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Epictetus</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">50 – 135 AD · Former Slave, Stoic Philosopher</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>What is death? A scary mask. Take it off — see, it doesn't bite.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Epictetus, Discourses, Book II</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet X — <strong>Live Like You Will Die. Because You Will.</strong> Epictetus stripped death of its power by refusing to dress it up in fear. A Grithosian does the same. Death is a bound — the final one. It is not a punishment. It is the structure that makes your time here matter. Use it as fuel, not as a cage.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>It is difficulties that show what men are.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Epictetus, Discourses, Book I</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XI — <strong>Grieve Fully. Then Move.</strong> Epictetus did not teach people to avoid difficulty. He taught them that difficulty is the proving ground. Grief, loss, suffering — these are not the end of the story. They are the chapter that reveals who you really are. Feel everything. Then rise.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Benjamin Franklin</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1706 – 1790 · Founding Father, Inventor, Philosopher</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>If you would not be forgotten as soon as you are dead, either write things worth reading or do things worth the writing.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin, Poor Richard's Almanack</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XII — <strong>Build a Legacy That Stands in This Life.</strong> Franklin did both. He wrote things the world still reads and built things the world still uses. A Grithosian does not hope to be remembered. A Grithosian builds something worth remembering. Not for vanity — because the mark you leave proves you were here and it mattered.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>When you're finished changing, you're finished.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is the urgency of Pillar IV — <strong>you are not done yet.</strong> Franklin reinvented himself constantly — printer, scientist, diplomat, founder. He never stopped building. A Grithosian understands that the moment you stop growing, you have chosen to start dying. Legacy is not something you build once. It is something you build until your last breath.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Hide not your talents. They for use were made. What's a sundial in the shade?</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin, Poor Richard's Almanack</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This speaks to every Grithosian who feels alone or unseen. Your gifts are not for you alone. They are for the people your legacy will touch. Connection is built by sharing what you have — your talent, your time, your presence. A sundial in the shade serves no one. Step into the light. Be useful. That is how you build a life that outlasts you.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Heraclitus</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">535 – 475 BC · Greek Philosopher, "The Weeping Philosopher"</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Heraclitus of Ephesus was born into royalty, abdicated his hereditary kingship to his brother, and retreated to the mountains to think about the nature of reality. He concluded that the only constant is change — that the universe is a river of fire and flux, and that most human beings are asleep while they walk through it. The ancients called him "The Obscure" because his truths were hard to accept, and "The Weeping Philosopher" because he grieved for a humanity too distracted to see what was right in front of them.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>No man ever steps in the same river twice, for it's not the same river and he's not the same man.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Heraclitus, Fragment 41 (DK B12/B49a), as cited in Plato, Cratylus 402a</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet X — <strong>Live Like You Will Die. Because You Will.</strong> Heraclitus understood that you are already dying — every moment, the person you were ceases to exist and someone slightly different takes their place. A Grithosian does not pretend that time stands still. The river moves. You move with it. Every day is the only version of this day you will ever get. The man who steps into the river tomorrow is not the man reading these words now. Live accordingly.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>The soul is dyed the color of its thoughts. Think only on those things that are in line with your principles and can bear the light of day.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Heraclitus, Fragment 43 (DK B45/B115), as reconstructed in early Stoic sources</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XII — <strong>Build a Legacy That Stands in This Life.</strong> Heraclitus saw that legacy begins in the mind. Every thought you entertain colors the soul you leave behind. A Grithosian builds a legacy not just through action but through the quality of their inner life — thoughts that can bear the light of day, principles that hold under scrutiny. Your legacy is not only what you built. It is who you became while building it.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Out of every one hundred men, ten shouldn't even be there, eighty are just targets, nine are the real fighters, and we are lucky to have them, for they make the battle. Ah, but the one — one is a warrior — and he will bring the others back.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Heraclitus, widely attributed, preserved in military philosophical tradition</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XI — <strong>Grieve Fully. Then Move.</strong> Heraclitus saw that most people sleepwalk through life. But the one — the warrior — carries the grief of the battle and still brings others home. A Grithosian feels the full weight of loss. You grieve because the fight mattered. But you do not stay on the battlefield mourning when there are people counting on you to lead them back. Grieve fully. Then move. Others need you standing.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Viktor Frankl</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1905 – 1997 · Psychiatrist, Holocaust Survivor, Author</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Viktor Frankl survived Auschwitz, Dachau, and the systematic murder of his wife, mother, father, and brother. In the camps, stripped of everything — possessions, dignity, his own name — he discovered the one thing that could not be taken: the ability to choose his response. He emerged from the Holocaust and wrote Man's Search for Meaning in nine days. It has sold over sixteen million copies. His suffering did not destroy him. It proved his thesis.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Everything can be taken from a man but one thing: the last of the human freedoms — to choose one's attitude in any given set of circumstances, to choose one's own way.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Viktor Frankl, Man's Search for Meaning, Part I, 1946</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet X — <strong>Live Like You Will Die. Because You Will.</strong> Frankl wrote these words from inside a death camp — a place designed to strip human beings of everything, including hope. And yet he found the irreducible core: the freedom to choose your response. A Grithosian lives with that same urgency. Death is not theoretical. It was not theoretical for Frankl. Every moment you have the power to choose your attitude is a moment you are still alive. Use it.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>When we are no longer able to change a situation, we are challenged to change ourselves.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Viktor Frankl, Man's Search for Meaning, Part II, 1946</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XI — <strong>Grieve Fully. Then Move.</strong> Frankl lost everyone he loved. He could not change that. He could not bring them back. But he could change what he did with the grief. He turned the worst suffering in human history into a book that has given millions the will to keep living. A Grithosian grieves fully — you honor the loss because it was real. But then you move. You transform the grief into something that serves the living. That is not denial. That is the deepest form of courage.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>He who has a why to live can bear almost any how.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Viktor Frankl, Man's Search for Meaning, Part I, 1946 (quoting Nietzsche, Twilight of the Idols)</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XII — <strong>Build a Legacy That Stands in This Life.</strong> Frankl survived because he had a why — the unfinished manuscript, the patients who needed him, the truths that had to be told. A Grithosian builds a legacy not for fame but because the legacy itself becomes the reason to endure. When you are building something that matters, you can survive almost anything. Your why is your anchor. Without it, every hardship is pointless suffering. With it, every hardship is raw material for something that outlasts you.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Friedrich Nietzsche</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1844 – 1900 · German Philosopher</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Nietzsche wrote in isolation, in chronic pain, largely ignored by the academic establishment — and produced ideas that detonated across the twentieth century. He declared God dead not in celebration but as a warning, and argued that suffering is not the enemy of meaning but its raw material.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>He who has a why to live for can bear almost any how.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Friedrich Nietzsche, Twilight of the Idols, "Maxims and Arrows," #12</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XII — <strong>Build a Legacy That Stands in This Life.</strong> Nietzsche understood that meaning is not given — it is forged. A Grithosian builds something worth suffering for. When your why is clear and powerful, you can endure almost any how. The legacy becomes the anchor.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Søren Kierkegaard</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1813 – 1855 · Danish Philosopher, Theologian</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Kierkegaard broke off his engagement to the woman he loved because he believed his calling demanded total devotion, then spent the rest of his short life writing about anxiety, despair, and the leap of faith. He is considered the father of existentialism — a man who stared into the abyss and chose to jump.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>The most painful state of being is remembering the future, particularly the one you'll never see.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Søren Kierkegaard, attributed, from his journals</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet X — <strong>Live Like You Will Die. Because You Will.</strong> Kierkegaard felt the weight of mortality intensely — every unrealized possibility, every path not taken. A Grithosian uses that weight as fuel. The future you'll never see makes the present you have sacred. Act accordingly.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Rumi</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1207 – 1273 · Persian Poet, Sufi Mystic</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Rumi was a respected Islamic scholar until he met a wandering mystic named Shams and his entire world cracked open. He poured his grief, ecstasy, and longing into poetry that has been translated into every major language — proving that the wound is where the light enters.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>The wound is the place where the Light enters you.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Rumi, from the Mathnavi</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XI — <strong>Grieve Fully. Then Move.</strong> Rumi understood that suffering is not the end of the story — it is the crack where transformation begins. A Grithosian does not hide from the wound. You honor it. You let it break you open. Because that is where the light gets in.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Khalil Gibran</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1883 – 1931 · Lebanese-American Poet, Philosopher, Artist</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Gibran left Lebanon at twelve, buried his mother, brother, and sister within a few years, and channeled that loss into The Prophet — a book that has sold over one hundred million copies. He wrote about love, death, freedom, and pain with the authority of someone who had lived all four.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Out of suffering have emerged the strongest souls; the most massive characters are seared with scars.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Khalil Gibran, attributed, widely cited</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XI — <strong>Grieve Fully. Then Move.</strong> Gibran did not hide his scars — he wore them as proof of what he had survived. A Grithosian understands that the strongest souls are forged in the fire of loss. Feel everything. Then stand up. The scars are not your weakness. They are your credentials.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Fyodor Dostoevsky</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1821 – 1881 · Russian Novelist</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Dostoevsky was arrested for political subversion, stood before a firing squad, and received a last-second reprieve — a mock execution designed to break him. It didn't. He spent the next thirty years in debt, in seizures, and in genius, writing novels that mapped the darkest corridors of the human soul.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Pain and suffering are always inevitable for a large intelligence and a deep heart.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Fyodor Dostoevsky, Crime and Punishment, Part I, Chapter 1</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet X — <strong>Live Like You Will Die. Because You Will.</strong> Dostoevsky did not promise an easy life for those who think deeply and feel much. A Grithosian accepts this. The capacity to build something meaningful comes with the capacity to suffer for it. That is not a bug. That is the design.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Albert Camus</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1913 – 1960 · French-Algerian Novelist, Philosopher</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Camus grew up fatherless and poor in colonial Algeria, contracted tuberculosis as a teenager, and went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature at forty-four. He argued that life is absurd — and that the proper response is not despair but revolt: to keep pushing the boulder uphill, fully aware it will roll back down.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>In the midst of winter, I found there was, within me, an invincible summer.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Albert Camus, "Return to Tipasa," Summer, 1954</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XII — <strong>Build a Legacy That Stands in This Life.</strong> Camus discovered that even in the darkest circumstances, there is something within you that cannot be broken. A Grithosian builds from that invincible core — not because life promises meaning, but because you create it. The absurd is not the enemy. It is the arena.
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

